Author-Name:    Feldstein, Martin S
Title:   Should Social Security Benefits Be Means Tested? 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 468-84
Issue: 3
Volume: 95
Year: 1987
Month:  June 
Abstract:
  Social-security retirement benefits distort the saving decisions of
 workers who are rational enough to save for their future. Since the
 implicit rate of return in an unfunded social-security program is less
 than the marginal product of capital, the resulting decline in saving
 causes a welfare loss. The present paper examines the conditions under
 which the welfare loss can be reduced by replacing the current universal
 social-security program with a means-tested program that pays benefits
 only to those individuals with little or no other retirement income or
 assets.  Copyright 1987 by University of Chicago Press.
